{"title_page": "Metro Pino Su\u00e1rez", "text_new": "{{short description|Mexico City metro station}}\n{{Infobox station \n| symbol_location = mexicocity \n| symbol          = \n| name            = [[File:Metro Pino Su\u00e1rez pictogram.svg|25px]] Pino Su\u00e1rez\n| type            = [[Mexico City Metro|STC]] [[rapid transit]]\n| style           = Mexico City Metro\n| style2          = 1 2 \n| image           = Pino_Suarez_Line_2_Platforms.jpg\n| image_caption   = Line 2 platforms\n| address         = \n| country         = \n| coordinates     = {{Coord|19.425336|N|99.132943|W|region:MX-DIF_type:railwaystation|display=it}}\n| elevation       = \n| other           = [[File:Mexico City Metrob\u00fas Line 4 icon.svg|16px|link=Mexico City Metrob\u00fas Line 4]]\n| structure       = Underground\n| platform        = 4 side platforms\n| depth           = \n| levels          = \n| tracks          = 4\n| parking         = \n| bicycle         = \n| opened          = {{rint|mexicocity|1}} 4 September 1969<br />{{rint|mexicocity|2}} 1 August 1970\n| closed          = \n| rebuilt         = \n| electrified     = \n| ADA             = Yes\n| code            = \n| owned           = \n| operator        = \n| zone            = \n| smartcardname   = \n| smartcardstatus = \n| former          = \n| passengers      = \n| pass_year       = \n| pass_percent    = \n| pass_system     = \n| mpassengers     = \n| services        = {{Adjacent stations|system=Mexico City Metro\n|line1=1|left1=Isabel la Cat\u00f3lica|right1=Merced\n|line2=2|left2=Z\u00f3calo|right2=San Antonio Abad}}\n| map_locator     = \n}}\n'''Metro Pino Su\u00e1rez''' is a [[metro station|station]] on [[Mexico City Metro Line 1|Line 1]] and [[Mexico City Metro Line 2|Line 2]] of the [[Mexico City Metro]] system.<ref name=\"metro\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.metro.df.gob.mx/red/estacion.html?id=10|title=Pino Su\u00e1rez|language=Spanish|accessdate=14 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110915133511/http://www.metro.df.gob.mx/red/estacion.html?id=10|archivedate=15 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"archambault\">{{Cite web|last=Archambault|first=Richard|url=http://mexicometro.org/metro/line1/pino-suarez/|title=Pino Su\u00e1rez (Line 1) &raquo;  Mexico City Metro System|accessdate=14 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"archambault_line2\">{{Cite web|last=Archambault|first=Richard|url=http://mexicometro.org/metro/line2/pino-suarez/|title=Pino Su\u00e1rez (Line 2) &raquo;  Mexico City Metro System|accessdate=14 August 2011}}</ref>  It is located in the [[Cuauht\u00e9moc, D.F.|Cuauht\u00e9moc]] borough of [[Mexico City]], on the southern part of the [[Centro (Mexico City)|city centre]].<ref name=\"metro\"/>\n\n==Iconography==\nThe station is named after [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Pino Su\u00e1rez]], Vice President of Mexico during the term of [[Francisco I. Madero]] (1911&ndash;1913).<ref name=\"metro\"/>  However, the station logo depicts a pyramid dedicated to [[Ehecatl]], the [[Aztec mythology|Aztec god]] of [[wind]].<ref name=\"metro\"/><ref name=\"archambault\"/><ref name=\"archambault_line2\"/>  This pyramid was discovered in the early construction of the station and it can be seen on display along the main transfer corridor.<ref name=\"metro\"/>\n\n==General information==\nThe Ehecatl pyramid was found during the construction of the station in 1967. While excavating was unearthed a round-shaped altar and was decided to let the pyramid remains and allow the National Institute of Archeology and History (INAH) to preserve and maintain it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mexicanroutes.com/pyramid-of-pino-suarez/|title=Pyramid of Pino Suarez|publisher=\"Mexican Routes\" [mexicanroutes.com]}}</ref>\n\nThis pyramid is the smallest archaeological zone in Mexico and is thought to have been part of a larger ceremonial center. The Ehecatl pyramid has 4 structural construction stages and it counts on a circular base that functioned as a pedestal for the deity placed at the top. Inside the pyramid have been found a few offerings.\n\nMetro Pino Su\u00e1rez was opened on 5 September 1969.<ref name=\"monroy_history\">{{Cite web|last=Monroy|first=Marco|editor-last=Schwandl|editor-first=Robert|url=http://www.urbanrail.net/am/mexi/mex-history.htm|title=Opening Dates for Mexico City's Subway|accessdate=14 August 2011}}</ref> The station is an important link to the centre of the city.  It was the first transfer station of the network and today it connects the two busiest lines.  Pino Su\u00e1rez has many corridors, the most notable among them being the Pasaje Z\u00f3calo\u2013Pino Su\u00e1rez that connects with [[Metro Z\u00f3calo]] at the north side, filled with bookstores and a mini-cinema; other corridors have cultural displays and temporary exhibitions.  The station also has an information desk.<ref name=\"metro\"/>\n\n==Exits==\n===Line 1===\n*North: Av. Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Izazaga and Av. Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Pino Su\u00e1rez, [[Historic center of Mexico City|Col. Centro]] \n*West: Av. Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Izazaga and Av. Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Pino Su\u00e1rez, [[Historic center of Mexico City|Col. Centro]]\n\n===Line 2===\n*South: San Lucas street and Av. Fray Servando Teresa de Mier, [[Historic center of Mexico City|Col. Centro]] \n*North: Av. Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Izazaga and Calzada San Antonio Abad, [[Historic center of Mexico City|Col. Centro]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Metro Pino Suarez 01.jpg|Entry sign for Metro Pino Su\u00e1rez\nImage:EntranceMetroPinoSuarez.JPG|One entrance to Metro Pino Suarez\nImage:AdoratoriodeEh%C3%A9catlMetroPinoDF.JPG|Altar dedicated to the god [[Eh\u00e9catl]], located in the middle of Metro Pino Su\u00e1rez.  This altar was unearthed during construction of the station in 1967 where it remains to this day surrounded by the passageway between Lines 1 and 2\nImage:Pino Suarez Line 1 Platforms.jpg|Line 1 platforms\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Mexico City metro stations]]\n\n== References ==\n