ight1=Merced\n|line2=2|left2=Z\u00f3calo|right2=San Antonio Abad}}\n| map_locator     = \n}}\n'''Metro Pino Su\u00e1rez''' is a [[metro station|station]] on [[Mexico City Metro Line 1|Line 1]] and [[Mexico City Metro Line 2|Line 2]] of the [[Mexico City Metro]] system.<ref name=\"metro\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.metro.df.gob.mx/red/estacion.html?id=10|title=Pino Su\u00e1rez|language=Spanish|accessdate=14 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110915133511/http://www.metro.df.gob.mx/red/estacion.html?id=10|archivedate=15 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"archambault\">{{Cite web|last=Archambault|first=Richard|url=http://mexicometro.org/metro/line1/pino-suarez/|title=Pino Su\u00e1rez (Line 1) &raquo;  Mexico City Metro System|accessdate=14 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"archambault_line2\">{{Cite web|last=Archambault|first=Richard|url=http://mexicometro.org/metro/line2/pino-suarez/|title=Pino Su\u00e1rez (Line 2) &raquo;  Mexico City Metro System|accessdate=14 August 2011}}</ref>  It is located in the [[Cuauht\u00e9moc, D.F.|Cuauht\u00e9moc]] borough of [[Mexico City]], on the southern part of the [[Centro (Mexico City)|city centre]].<ref name=\"metro\"/>\n\n==Iconography==\nThe station is named after [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Pino Su\u00e1rez]], Vice President of Mexico during the term of [[Francisco I. Madero]] (1911&ndash;1913).<ref name=\"metro\"/>  However, the station logo depicts a pyramid dedicated to [[Ehecatl]], the [[Aztec mythology|Aztec god]] of [[wind]].<ref name=\"metro\"/><ref name=\"archambault\"/><ref name=\"archambault_line2\"/>  This pyramid was discovered in the early construction of the station and it can be seen on display along the main transfer corridor.<ref name=\"metro\"/>\n\n==General information==\nThe Ehecatl pyramid was found during the construction of the station in 1967. While excavating was unearthed a round-shaped altar and was decided to let the pyramid remains and allow the National Institute of Archeology and History (INAH) to preserve and maintain it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mexicanroutes.com/pyramid-of-pino-suarez/|title=Pyramid of Pino Suarez|publisher=\"Mexican Routes\" [mexicanroutes.com]}}</ref>\n\nThis pyramid is the smallest archaeological zone in Mexico and is thought to have been part of a larger ceremonial center. The Ehecatl pyramid has 4 structural construction stages and it counts on a circular base that functioned as a pedestal for the deity placed at the top. Inside the pyramid have been found a few offerings.\n\nMetro Pino Su\u00e1rez was opened on 5 September 1969.<ref name=\"monroy_history\">{{Cite web|last=Monroy|first=Marco|editor-last=Schwandl|editor-first=Robert|url=http://www.urbanrail.net/am/mexi/mex-history.htm|title=Opening Dates for Mexico City's Subway|accessdate=14 August 2011}}</ref> The station is an important link to the centre of the city.  It was the first transfer station of the network and today it connects the two busiest lines.  Pino Su\u00e1rez has many corridors, the most notable among them being the Pasaje Z\u00f3calo\u2013Pino Su\u00e1rez that connects with [[Metro Z\u00f3calo]] at the north side, filled with bookstores and a mini-cinema; other corridors have cultural displays and temporary exhibitions.  The station also has an information desk.<ref name=\"metro\"/>\n\n==Exits==\n===Line 1===\n*North: Av. Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Izazaga and Av. Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Pino Su\u00e1rez, [[Historic center of Mexico City|Col. Centro]] \n*West: Av. Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Izazaga and Av. Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Pino Su\u00e1rez, [[Historic center of Mexico City|Col. Centro]]\n\n===Line 2===\n*South: San Lucas street and Av. Fray Servando Teresa de Mier, [[Historic center of Mexico City|Col. Centro]] \n*North: Av. Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Izazaga and Calzada San Antonio Abad, [[Historic center of Mexico City|Col. Centro]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Metro Pino Suarez 01.jpg|Entry sign for Metro Pino Su\u00e1rez\nImage:EntranceMetroPinoSuarez.JPG|One entrance to Metro Pino Suarez\nImage:AdoratoriodeEh%C3%A9catlMetroPinoDF.JPG|Altar dedicated to the god [[Eh\u00e9catl]], located in the middle of Metro Pino Su\u00e1rez.  This altar was unearthed during construction of the station in 1967 where it remains to this day surrounded by the passageway between Lines 1 and 2\nImage:Pino Suarez Line 1 Platforms.jpg|Line 1 platforms\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Mexico City metro stations]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://mexicanroutes.com/pyramid-of-pino-suarez/ Pyramid of Pino Suarez], \"Mexican Routes\" [mexicanroutes.com]\n* {{commonscat-inline|Pino Su\u00e1rez (station)}}\n{{Cuauht\u00e9moc, Mexico City}}\n{{MxMetro}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Metro Pino Suarez}}\n[[Category:Mexico City metro stations|Pino Suarez]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1969]]\n[[Category:1969 establishments in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1970]]\n[[Category:1970 establishments in Mexico]]\n", "name_user": "Cocu15", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metro_Pino_Su%C3%A1rez"}
{"title_page": "River States Conference", "text_new": "{{Infobox Athletic Conference\n|name = River States Conference\n|short_name = RSC\n|established = 1916\n|logo = River States Conference logo.png\n|logo_size = 175\n|association = [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]]\n|division = Division I\nDivision II\n|subdivision =\n|members = 12 (13 in 2020)\n|sports = 17\n|mens = 8\n|womens = 9\n|region = [[Eastern United States|Eastern]]\n|former_names =\n|hq_city = Middletown\n|hq_state = Ohio\n|commissioner = Michael Schell\n|since = March 15, 2018\n|website = {{url|www.riverstatesconference.com}}\n|color = #003F7F\n|font_color = white\n|map = River States Conference map.svg\n|map_size = 250\n}}\n\nThe '''River States Conference''' ('''RSC'''), formerly known as '''Kentucky Intercollegiate Athletic Conference''' ('''KIAC'''), is a collegiate athletic conference with membership in the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics]] (NAIA). Although it was historically a [[Kentucky]]-only conference, it has now expanded to include members in [[Indiana]], [[Ohio]], [[Pennsylvania]], and [[West Virginia]], and at various times in the past has also had members in [[Missouri]], [[Tennessee]], and [[Virginia]].\n\nIn March 2016, the KIAC announced it would change its name to the River States Conference, effective July 1, 2016, to better reflect its membership, which has expanded beyond Kentucky and now includes members in Pennsylvania, Indiana, Ohio and West Virginia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kiacsports.com/article/2735.php|title=KIAC announces River States Conference as new name, unveils new logo|date=March 4, 2016|accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Member schools==\n===Current members===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Institution\n!Location\n!Founded\n!Type\n!Enrollment\n!Nickname\n!Joined\n|-\n![[Alice Lloyd College]]\n|[[Pippa Passes, Kentucky]]\n|1923\n|[[Private university|Private]] ([[Nondenominational Christianity|Christian]])\n|600\n|[[Alice Lloyd Eagles|Eagles]]\n|1983;<br>2005{{efn|group=cm|Alice Lloyd left the KIAC in 1992 and rejoined in 2005.}}\n|-\n![[Asbury University]]\n|[[Wilmore, Kentucky]]\n|1890\n|Private ([[Christian College Consortium|Christian]])\n|1,300\n|[[Asbury Eagles|Eagles]]\n|1971\n|-\n![[Brescia University]]\n|[[Owensboro, Kentucky]]\n|1950\n|Private ([[Catholic Church|Catholic]])\n|1,100\n|[[Brescia Bearcats|Bearcats]]\n|1984\n|-\n![[Carlow University]]\n|[[Pittsburgh|Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]]\n|1929\n|Private (Catholic)\n|2,400\n|[[Carlow Celtics|Celtics]]\n|2012\n|-\n![[Indiana University East]]\n|[[Richmond, Indiana]]\n|1971\n|[[Public university|Public]]\n|2,700\n|[[Indiana\u2013East Red Wolves|Red Wolves]]\n|2007\n|-\n![[Indiana University Kokomo]]\n|[[Kokomo, Indiana]]\n|1945\n|Public\n|3,719\n|[[Indiana\u2013Kokomo Cougars|Cougars]]\n|2013\n|-\n![[Indiana University Southeast]]\n|[[New Albany, Indiana]]\n|1941\n|Public\n|6,840\n|[[Indiana\u2013Southeast Grenadiers|Grenadiers]]\n|1994\n|-\n![[Midway University]]\n|[[Midway, Kentucky]]\n|1847\n|Private [[Christian Church (Disciples of Christ)|Disciples of Christ]])\n|1,800\n|[[Midway Eagles|Eagles]]\n|1991{{efn|group=cm|Midway was a women's college until 2016.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.midway.edu/2016/05/16/midway-university-trustees-vote-accept-men-daytime-undergraduate-programs/ |title=Midway University Trustees vote to accept men into its daytime undergraduate programs |publisher=Midway University |date=May 16, 2016 |accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref> The school began sponsoring men's sports in 2017.}}\n|-\n![[Ohio Christian University]]\n|[[Circleville, Ohio]]\n|1948\n|Private ([[Churches of Christ in Christian Union|CCCU]])\n|3,300\n|[[Ohio Christian Trailblazers|Trailblazers]]\n|2015\n|-\n![[Point Park University]]\n|[[Pittsburgh|Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]]\n|1960\n|Private ([[Nonsectarian]])\n|3,376\n|[[Point Park Pioneers|Pioneers]]\n|2012\n|-\n!{{sort|Rio Grande|[[University of Rio Grande]]}}\n|[[Rio Grande, Ohio]]\n|1876\n|Private (Nonsectarian)\n|1,893\n|[[Rio Grande RedStorm|RedStorm]]\n|1964;<br>2014{{efn|group=cm|Rio Grande left the KIAC in 1971 and rejoined in 2014.}}\n|-\n![[West Virginia University Institute of Technology]]\n|[[Beckley, West Virginia]]\n|1895\n|Public\n|2,252\n|[[West Virginia Tech Golden Bears|Golden Bears]]\n|2015\n|}\n\n{{notelist|group=cm}}\n\n===Future members===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Institution\n!Location\n!Founded\n!Type\n!Enrollment\n!Nickname\n!Joining\n|-\n![[Oakland City University]]\n|[[Oakland City, Indiana]]\n|1885\n|Private ([[General Association of General Baptists|Baptist]])\n|2,350\n|Mighty Oaks\n|2020<ref name =\"2020NAIAnewmembers\">{{cite news |author=VSN Staff |title=NAIA Approves Five Institutions for Membership |url=http://www.victorysportsnetwork.com/Clip/news/naia-approves-five-institutions-for-membership.htm |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |publisher=Victory Sports Network |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Former members===\nSchool names and nicknames reflect those used in the final school year each institution was a conference member.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Institution\n!Location\n!Founded\n!Nickname\n!Joined\n!Left\n!Current<br>Conference\n|-\n![[Bellarmine University|Bellarmine College]]{{efn|group=fm|Known as Bellarmine University since 2000.}}\n|[[Louisville, Kentucky]]\n|1950\n|[[Bellarmine Knights|Knights]]\n|1951\n|1964\n|[[Great Lakes Valley Conference|Great Lakes Valley]]<br>([[NCAA Division II|NCAA D-II]]){{efn|group=fm|Bellarmine will join the [[NCAA Division I]] [[Atlantic Sun Conference|ASUN Conference]] in 2020.}}\n|-\n![[Berea College]]\n|[[Berea, Kentucky]]\n|1855\n|[[Berea Mountaineers|Mountaineers]]\n|1926\n|2014\n|[[USA South Athletic Conference|USA South]]<br>([[NCAA Division III|NCAA D-III]])\n|-\n![[Bethel University (Tennessee)|Bethel College]]{{efn|group=fm|Know