y University#Athletics|Mighty Oaks]]\n|1968\n|1975\n|[[NCAA Division II independent schools#All-sport independents|Independent]]<br>([[NCAA Division II|NCAA D-II]])\n|-\n![[Ogden College]]\n|[[Bowling Green, Kentucky]]\n|1906\n|Eagles\n|1926\n|1927\n|nowrap|Merged in 1927 with<br>[[Western Kentucky University]]\n|-\n!{{sort|Pikeville|[[University of Pikeville]]}}\n|[[Pikeville, Kentucky]]\n|1889\n|[[Pikeville Bears|Bears]]\n|1958\n|2000\n|[[Mid-South Conference|Mid-South]]\n|-\n!{{sort|Saint Louis|[[St. Louis College of Pharmacy]]}}\n|{{sort|Saint Louis|[[St. Louis|St. Louis, Missouri]]}}\n|1864\n|[[St. Louis Pharmacy Eutectics|Eutectics]]\n|2003\n|2014\n|[[American Midwest Conference|American Midwest]]\n|-\n![[Spalding University]]\n|[[Louisville, Kentucky]]\n|1814\n|[[Spalding Golden Eagles|Golden Eagles]]\n|1992\n|2007\n|{{sort|Saint Louis|[[St. Louis Intercollegiate Athletic Conference|St. Louis]]}}<br>([[NCAA Division III|NCAA D-III]])\n|-\n![[Thomas More University|Thomas More College]]{{efn|group=fm|Known as Thomas More University since 2018.}}\n|[[Crestview Hills, Kentucky]]\n|1921\n|[[Thomas More Saints|Saints]]\n|1955\n|1991\n| [[Mid-South Conference|Mid-South]]\n|-\n![[Transylvania University]]\n|[[Lexington, Kentucky]]\n|1780\n|[[Transylvania Pioneers|Pioneers]]\n|1926\n|2001\n|[[Heartland Collegiate Athletic Conference|Heartland Collegiate]]<br>([[NCAA Division III|NCAA D-III]])\n|-\n![[Union College (Kentucky)|Union College]]\n|[[Barbourville, Kentucky]]\n|1879\n|[[Union College Bulldogs|Bulldogs]]\n|1933\n|1995\n|[[Appalachian Athletic Conference|Appalachian]]\n|-\n![[Western Kentucky University|Western Kentucky State Teachers College]]{{efn|group=fm|Renamed Western Kentucky State College immediately after leaving the KIAC, and known as Western Kentucky University since 1966.}}\n|[[Bowling Green, Kentucky]]\n|1906\n|[[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers and Lady Toppers|Hilltoppers]]\n|1926\n|1948\n|[[Conference USA]]<br>([[NCAA Division I|NCAA D-I]])\n|}\n\n{{notelist|group=fm}}\n\n==Conference sports==\n\nThe River States Conference currently fields 17 sports (8 men's and 9 women's):\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Conference sports\n!Sport||Men's||Women's\n|-\n|{{left}}[[Baseball]] || {{Y}} ||\n|-\n|{{left}}[[Basketball]] || {{Y}} || {{Y}}\n|-\n|{{left}}[[Cross country running|Cross Country]] || {{Y}} || {{Y}}\n|-\n|{{left}}[[Golf]] || {{Y}} || {{Y}}\n|-\n|{{left}}[[Soccer]] || {{Y}} || {{Y}}\n|-\n|{{left}}[[Softball]] || || {{Y}}\n|-\n|{{left}}[[Tennis]] || {{Y}} || {{Y}}\n|-\n|{{left}}[[Track and field|Track & Field Indoor]] || {{Y}} || {{Y}}\n|-\n|{{left}}[[Track and field|Track & Field Outdoor]] || {{Y}} || {{Y}}\n|-\n|{{left}}[[Volleyball]] || || {{Y}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.riverstatesconference.com}}\n\n{{River States Conference navbox}}\n{{NAIA conference navbox}}\n\n[[Category:River States Conference| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Athletic Conference\n|name = River States Conference\n|short_name = RSC\n|established = 1916\n|logo = River States Conference logo.png\n|logo_size = 175\n|association = [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]]\n|division = Division I\nDivision II\n|subdivision =\n|members = 12 (13 in 2020)\n|sports = 17\n|mens = 8\n|womens = 9\n|region = [[Eastern United States|Eastern]]\n|former_names =\n|hq_city = Middletown\n|hq_state = Ohio\n|commissioner = Michael Schell\n|since = March 15, 2018\n|website = {{url|www.riverstatesconference.com}}\n|color = #003F7F\n|font_color = white\n|map = River States Conference map.svg\n|map_size = 250\n}}\n\nThe '''River States Conference''' ('''RSC'''), formerly known as '''Kentucky Intercollegiate Athletic Conference''' ('''KIAC'''), is a collegiate athletic conference with membership in the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics]] (NAIA). Although it was historically a [[Kentucky]]-only conference, it has now expanded to include members in [[Indiana]], [[Ohio]], [[Pennsylvania]], and [[West Virginia]], and at various times in the past has also had members in [[Missouri]], [[Tennessee]], and [[Virginia]].\n\nIn March 2016, the KIAC announced it would change its name to the River States Conference, effective July 1, 2016, to better reflect its membership, which has expanded beyond Kentucky and now includes members in Pennsylvania, Indiana, Ohio and West Virginia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kiacsports.com/article/2735.php|title=KIAC announces River States Conference as new name, unveils new logo|date=March 4, 2016|accessdate=March 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Member schools==\n===Current members===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Institution\n!Location\n!Founded\n!Type\n!Enrollment\n!Nickname\n!Joined\n|-\n![[Alice Lloyd College]]\n|[[Pippa Passes, Kentucky]]\n|1923\n|[[Private university|Private]] ([[Nondenominational Christianity|Christian]])\n|600\n|[[Alice Lloyd Eagles|Eagles]]\n|1983;<br>2005{{efn|group=cm|Alice Lloyd left the KIAC in 1992 and rejoined in 2005.}}\n|-\n![[Asbury University]]\n|[[Wilmore, Kentucky]]\n|1890\n|Private ([[Christian College Consortium|Christian]])\n|1,300\n|[[Asbury Eagles|Eagles]]\n|1971\n|-\n![[Brescia University]]\n|[[Owensboro, Kentucky]]\n|1950\n|Private ([[Catholic Church|Catholic]])\n|1,100\n|[[Brescia Bearcats|Bearcats]]\n|1984\n|-\n![[Carlow University]]\n|[[Pittsburgh|Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]]\n|1929\n|Private (Catholic)\n|2,400\n|[[Carlow Celtics|Celtics]]\n|2012\n|-\n![[Indiana University East]]\n|[[Richmond, Indiana]]\n|1971\n|[[Public university|Public]]\n|2,700\n|[[Indiana\u2013East Red Wolves|Red Wolves]]\n|2007\n|-\n![[Indiana University Kokomo]]\n|[[Kokomo, Indiana]]\n|1945\n|Public\n|3,719\n|[[Indiana\u2013Kokomo Cougars|Cougars]]\n|2013\n|-\n![[Indiana University Southeast]]\n|[[New Albany, Indiana]]\n|1941\n|Public\n|6,840\n|[[Indiana\u2013Southeast Grenadiers|Grenadiers]]\n|1994\n|-\n![[Midway University]]\n|[[Midway, Kentucky]]\n|1847\n|Private [[Christian Church (Disciples of Christ)|Disciples of Christ]])\n|1,800\n|[[Midway Eagles|Eagles]]\n|1991{{efn|group=cm|Midway was a women's college until 2016.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.midway.edu/2016/05/16/midway-university-trustees-vote-accept-men-daytime-undergraduate-programs/ |title=Midway University Trustees vote to accept men into its daytime undergraduate programs |publisher=Midway University |date=May 16, 2016 |accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref> The school began sponsoring men's sports in 2017.}}\n|-\n![[Ohio Christian University]]\n|[[Circleville, Ohio]]\n|1948\n|Private ([[Churches of Christ in Christian Union|CCCU]])\n|3,300\n|[[Ohio Christian Trailblazers|Trailblazers]]\n|2015\n|-\n![[Point Park University]]\n|[[Pittsburgh|Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]]\n|1960\n|Private ([[Nonsectarian]])\n|3,376\n|[[Point Park Pioneers|Pioneers]]\n|2012\n|-\n!{{sort|Rio Grande|[[University of Rio Grande]]}}\n|[[Rio Grande, Ohio]]\n|1876\n|Private (Nonsectarian)\n|1,893\n|[[Rio Grande RedStorm|RedStorm]]\n|1964;<br>2014{{efn|group=cm|Rio Grande left the KIAC in 1971 and rejoined in 2014.}}\n|-\n![[West Virginia University Institute of Technology]]\n|[[Beckley, West Virginia]]\n|1895\n|Public\n|2,252\n|[[West Virginia Tech Golden Bears|Golden Bears]]\n|2015\n|}\n\n{{notelist|group=cm}}\n\n===Future members===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Institution\n!Location\n!Founded\n!Type\n!Enrollment\n!Nickname\n!Joined\n|-\n![[Oakland City University]]\n|[[Oakland City, Indiana]]\n|1885\n|Private ([[General Association of General Baptists|Baptist]])\n|2,350\n|Mighty Oaks\n|2020<ref name =\"2020NAIAnewmembers\">{{cite news |author=VSN Staff |title=NAIA Approves Five Institutions for Membership |url=http://www.victorysportsnetwork.com/Clip/news/naia-approves-five-institutions-for-membership.htm |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |publisher=Victory Sports Network |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Form